isPermaLink="false">http://creditshout.com/?p=13263</guid> <description><![CDATA[<br/>Paying with a credit card is about to get a whole lot more popular for BOA customers. Bank of America has announced plans to charge a $5 monthly debit card fee. This is yet another move among card issuers in response to the new regulations on swipe fees, which are expected to reduce revenue. The [...]]]></description> <content:encoded><![CDATA[<br/><p><img
src="http://creditshout.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/52755570-260x186.jpg" alt="" title="52755570" width="260" height="186" class="photo" />Paying with a credit card is about to get a whole lot more popular for BOA customers.  Bank of America has announced plans to charge a $5 monthly debit card fee. This is yet another move among card issuers in response to the new regulations on swipe fees, which are expected to reduce revenue.</p><p>The fee will be levied on customers who have basic checking accounts. Customers must use the card to make purchases in order to incur the fee. Those who do not use a debit card or <a
href="http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/sep/29/bank-america-charge-5month-debit-cards/" target="_blank">only use it for ATM transactions</a> in a given month will not be charged the fee. Customers with premium checking accounts will not be charged the fee, as well.</p><p>The fee will be implemented in select states in January. The states to be affected first have yet to be announced.</p><p><span
id="more-13263"></span>Prior to Warren Buffet’s bailout of the company recently, they had significant <a
href="http://www.mercurynews.com/breaking-news/ci_19003931" target="_blank">setbacks</a>, perhaps adding to the desire for this fee. In addition to the new regulations, failed mortgages and lawsuits have eaten away at the company. Their stock has lost almost half of it’s value this year. Additionally, Bank of America announced plans to cut approximately 30,000 jobs.</p><p>So, if you have a Bank of America debit card that is tied to a basic checking account, you’ll have to pay a $5 monthly fee for anything in excess of ATM transactions. That comes out to $60 annually if you use it each month for purchases. That’s not the end of the world, but it’s another $60 down the drain in a tight economy &#8211; on top of declining rewards. Will you keep your Bank of America debit card or will you shop around for a better deal?</p><div
class="bigheader">How To Get Rid of The $5 Monthly Fee</div><p>In the past, many fees could be waved simply by contacting customer support, however something tells me that isn&#8217;t going to cut it with this new universal fee.</p><p>The first, most obvious answer is to just switch banks.  However I would actually hold off to see which banks end up implementing a debit card fee because of the new swipe fee regulations.  Bank of America wasn&#8217;t the first, and they won&#8217;t be the last to implement this new policy.</p><p>There is also the option of getting rid of your BOA debit card, while keeping your account.  Ditching your debit card completely may be a hard adjustment but it&#8217;s not impossible. You can pay your bills and online retailers by electronic check which is a great alternative to using a debit card.  Many popular online retailers <a
href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=15399401">including Amazon support this feature</a>.  You can then use a credit card for all of the other purchases that you usually make with your debit card, and pay the card off in full each month with an electronic transfer from BOA.</p><p>At the end of the day, it is completely possible to live without a debit card, and with attractive rewards programs offered by cards like <a
href="http://creditshout.com/blue-cash-from-american-express-review/">American Express Blue Cash</a> and <a
href="http://creditshout.com/chase-freedom-credit-card-review/">Chase Freedom</a> you may even be better off.  If you do go the credit card route, just use the card responsibly and make sure to pay off your balance in full each month.</p> ]]></content:encoded> <wfw:commentRss>http://creditshout.com/how-to-get-rid-of-the-bank-of-america-5-monthly-debit-card-fee/feed/</wfw:commentRss> <slash:comments>0</slash:comments> </item> <item><title>How To Get Companion Pass Status With Southwest Rapid Rewards</title><link>http://creditshout.com/how-to-get-companion-pass-status-with-southwest-rapid-rewards/</link> <comments>http://creditshout.com/how-to-get-companion-pass-status-with-southwest-rapid-rewards/#comments</comments> <pubDate>Thu, 29 Sep 2011 20:54:32 +0000</pubDate> <dc:creator>Clay Wyatt</dc:creator> <category><![CDATA[General]]></category> <guid
isPermaLink="false">http://creditshout.com/?p=13248</guid> <description><![CDATA[<br/>Do you take Southwest up on it’s slogan of “You are now free to move about the country”? Do you find yourself flying on the airline weekly &#8211; or even more? If so, you may be eligible for Companion Pass status. What is Companion Pass Status? Companion Pass status means that a designated companion will [...]]]></description> <content:encoded><![CDATA[<br/><p><img
src="http://creditshout.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/southwest737approach-260x173.jpg" alt="" title="southwest737approach" width="260" height="173" class="photo" />Do you take Southwest up on it’s slogan of “You are now free to move about the country”? Do you find yourself flying on the airline weekly &#8211; or even more? If so, you may be eligible for Companion Pass status.</p><div
class="bigheader">What is Companion Pass Status?</div><p>Companion Pass status means that a designated companion will fly for free for the remainder of the year in which this status is achieved and the entire following year. The companion must be 1 person, so you won’t be able to have a different companion fly for free each time. However, there is 1 caveat, as the companion may be changed up to 3 times during the period that the Companion Pass is valid. So, if you were hoping to fly to New York City with your spouse next week and then take your daughter to see Grandma in Florida in a few months, you could do so with a bit of effort. It will take some time to do so, as the request must be mailed to Southwest in writing along with the current pass. Note that, while the ticket is free for the companion, he or she may still incur a government-imposed security fee of up to $10 per round trip.</p><p><span
id="more-13248"></span>It is also important to note that no Rapid Rewards points will be given to your companion during flights in which your Companion Pass is used. While this may seem like a no-brainer, this could come into play if you were, say, hoping to score some free flights for your spouse who is also enrolled in the Rapid Rewards program. He or she could still fly free, but would not accumulate points in the process.</p><div
class="bigheader">How to Achieve Companion Pass Status</div><p>To achieve Companion Pass status, Rapid Rewards members must earn 110,000 qualifying points or fly 100 1-way flights in a calendar year. For purposes of this offer, a 1-way flight includes connecting flights. So, if you are flying from Cleveland to San Jose and stop in Los Angeles, you’ll get credit for 1 flight. If you fly back, you’ll then have a round trip for a total of 2 flights. You’ll have to fly 50 round trips to qualify for this offer, so this is geared toward frequent flyers.</p><p>Once you’ve hit the points or flights threshold, Southwest Airlines will mail you a postcard notifying you of your eligibility. At this point, you may send in the information regarding your companion. After your companion is designated, you’ll received your <a
href="http://www.southwest.com/html/customer-service/faqs.html?topic=rapid_rewards_program_terms_and_conditions" target="_blank">Companion Pass</a> within 10 business days.</p><div
class="bigheader">Earning Points With The Rapid Rewards Card</div><p><div
