isPermaLink="false">http://creditshout.com/?p=13201</guid> <description><![CDATA[<br/>So, you’re a frequent flyer and are a bit tired of sitting elbow-to-elbow with a stranger on your flights. You’ve flown on Delta for a while now and are accumulating Medallion Qualification Miles (MQMs) quickly. Once you hit certain threshold amounts with your MQMs, you will be entitled to various benefits, including complimentary seat upgrades. [...]]]></description> <content:encoded><![CDATA[<br/><p><img
src="http://creditshout.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/delta-e1317233163706-260x142.jpg" alt="" title="delta" width="260" height="142" class="photo" /></a>So, you’re a frequent flyer and are a bit tired of sitting elbow-to-elbow with a stranger on your flights. You’ve flown on Delta for a  while now and are accumulating Medallion Qualification Miles (MQMs) quickly. Once you hit certain threshold amounts with your MQMs, you will be entitled to various benefits, including complimentary seat upgrades. How do you go about doing so?</p><p>In order to qualify for complimentary upgrades, you’ll have to accumulate at least 25,000 MQMs. At this point, you will achieve Silver Medallion Status. As the typical Delta flight earns at least 500 MQMs (even if you travel less than that in actual miles), you should be able to reach this amount fairly quickly if you are frequent flyer. Many are multiplied by 1.5, so you’d actually receive, for example, 3,000 MQMs if you traveled 2,000 miles. At that rate, you’d hit 25,000 MQMs in just over eight round trips. <span
id="more-13201"></span></p><p>Here is the breakdown of the <a
href="http://www.delta.com/skymiles/about_skymiles/benefits_at_glance/upgrades/index.jsp" target="_blank">remaining thresholds and statuses</a>:</p><ul><li>50,000 MQMs &#8211; Gold Medallion Status</li><li>75,000 MQMs &#8211; Platinum Medallion Status</li><li>125,000 MQMs &#8211; Diamond Medallion Status</li></ul><p>Once you reach Silver Medallion Status, you will qualify for unlimited upgrades. Of course, the perks get better as your status rises, so you’ll stand to benefit more by moving up the ranks. Here is how upgrades are prioritized (all but priority 1 apply to class B, M, H, Q, K, L, U, T and E tickets) :</p><ul><li>Priority 1: All Medallion flyers on Y-class fares are cleared for upgrades at the time of ticketing</li><li>Priority 2: Diamond Medallion  flyers are cleared for upgrades 5 days prior to their flights</li><li>Priority 3: Platinum Medallion flyers are cleared for upgrades 5 days prior to their flights</li><li>Priority 4: Gold Medallion flyers are cleared for upgrades 3 days prior to their flights</li><li>Priority 5: Silver Medallion flyers are cleared 1 day prior to their flights</li><li>Priority 6: Companions are cleared within 24 hours of departure</li></ul><p>In addition, those paying with award tickets or the Pay with Miles program are given priority at each level after Diamond Medallion flyers are cleared. In other words, after Diamond Medallion flyers are cleared for their upgrades, those paying with award tickets or the Pay with Miles program are cleared next and this process repeats in steps 3 and 4 with the Platinum and Gold Medallions, respectively. Your chances of getting cleared for an upgrade decrease at each priority, so you’ll have a much better chance at getting an upgrade with Diamond Medallion Status than with Silver Medallion Status.</p><p>So, once you earn at least 25,000 MQMs, you’ll be eligible for complimentary upgrades with the Delta SkyMiles program. While I wouldn’t recommend going out and taking a bunch of random flights just to reach this amount, it will be a nice benefit if you fly enough to achieve it anyway. Of course, availability of seat upgrades is also an issue, so Diamond Medallion Status doesn’t mean you’ll be rubbing elbows with celebrities and corporate big-shots on every flight &#8211; and, even if you do sit next to them, you won‘t have to rub elbows with them in your comfortable seat! However, you will be able to fly more comfortably on some flights, which isn’t a bad perk to have if you’re in the air a lot.</p><p><div
